<TITLE> PILKHANA MUTINY TRIAL: Charge-framing starts May 9 </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Mar 16 (bdnews24.com)  The special court, set up in Darbar Hall to try 310 BDR men accused of the Pilkhana mutiny, has been adjourned until May 9 when the court will start framing charges against the suspected mutineers. The court, presided over by BDR director general Maj Gen Mainul Islam, sat between 10am and midday on Tuesday. All 310 defendents from 36 Rifles Battalion in the Dhaka Sector were produced in the court. Islam said that the accused would be allowed on May 9 to make a plea of self defence by themselves or through their lawyers. He asked those who have been detained in jails whether they were receiving half of their salaries as required by the rules. All detainees except one replied yes. who said that he had not received his salary for the month following the mutiny, The court ordered the commander of 36 rifles battalion to take appropriate measures on that matter. The trial of the alleged Pilkhana mutineers started on Feb 23 but was adjourned after just two days. It again resumed last Monday but was again adjourned All 310 accused are now in jail following the arrest of a further 69 men on Monday. Over 70 people, nearly 60 of them army officers deputed to the border force, were killed during the Pilkhana mutiny on Feb 25-26 2009. The government formed six special courts last year, including two in Dhaka, to try approximately 3,500 border guards who have been accused in 40 separate cases in connection with the Pilkhana mutiny and associated rebellions in different districts. 
